0–1487","1358–1405":"1358–1405","1385–1467":"1385–1467","1404":"1404","1358":"1358","1467":"1467","after 1405":"na 1405","1487":"1487","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1405":"1405","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Whitestaunton, Chard, Somerset, England":"Whitestaunton, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1405–1440":"1405–1440","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1430–1487":"1430–1487","1358–1405":"1358–1405","1385–1467":"1385–1467","1404":"1404","1358":"1358","1467":"1467","after 1405":"after 1405","1487":"1487","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1405":"1405","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Whitestaunton, Chard, Somerset, England":"Whitestaunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from any of various places called Alford, for example in Somerset, Cheshire and Lincolnshire. The first is named with the Old English female personal name <i>Ealdgȳth</i> + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. See also   Alvord  .","variant of   Halford   (or vice versa).","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Alvord","meanings":["English (southwestern): variant of   Alford   1; the spelling reflects the southwestern English dialect pronunciation.","History: This surname was brought to North America by Alexander Alvord, who came from Devon or Somerset to Windsor, CT, <i>c.</i> 1645. He had many prominent descendants."]},{"name":"Halford","meanings":["English (mainly Midlands): habitational name from any of various places called Halford. Most, for example those in Warwickshire, Devon, and Shropshire, or the lost place <i>Haleford</i> in Pembury (Kent), are named from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","English: variant of   Alford   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Allford","meanings":["English: variant of   Alford  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Grantham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, of uncertain origin. The final element is Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’; the first may be Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ or perhaps a personal name <i>Granta</i>, which probably originated as a byname meaning ‘snarler’. See also   Graham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Graham","meanings":["Transferred use of a Scottish surname, in origin a local name from Grantham in Lincolnshire. This is recorded in Domesday Book not only in its current form but also as <i>Grandham</i>, <i>Granham</i>, and <i>Graham</i>; it was apparently named as the ‘gravelly place’, from Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. The surname was taken to Scotland in the 12th century by  Sir William de Graham , founder of a famous clan. The earls of Montrose were among his descendants."]},{"name":"Granton","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name from any of several places named with the Old English elements <i>grāf</i> ‘grove’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. In the United States it seems to have been adopted as a given name in honour of the third Duke of Grafton,  Augustus Henry Fitzroy , who served as British Prime Minister  1767–70  and who favoured conciliation with the American colonies."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Grantham Alford was born in 1405, in Somerset, England, his father, Thomas De Ardene, was 47 and his mother, Elizabeth Pickering, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Frances Powell. He died in 1440, in Whitestaunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1405–1440":"1405–1440","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1430–1487":"1430–1487","1358–1405":"1358–1405","1385–1467":"1385–1467","1404":"1404","1358":"1358","1467":"1467","after 1405":"pärast 1405","1487":"1487","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1405":"1405","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Whitestaunton, Chard, Somerset, England":"Whitestaunton, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1405–1440":"1405–1440","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1430–1487":"1430–1487","1358–1405":"1358–1405","1385–1467":"1385–1467","1404":"1404","1358":"1358","1467":"1467","after 1405":"1405 jälkeen","1487":"1487","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1405":"1405","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Whitestaunton, Chard, Somerset, England":"Whitestaunton, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1405–1440":"1405–1440","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1430–1487":"1430–1487","1358–1405":"1358–1405","1385–1467":"1385–1467","1404":"1404","1358":"1358","1467":"1467","after 1405":"après 1405","1487":"1487","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1405":"1405","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Angleterre","Whitestaunton, Chard, Somerset, England":"Whitestaunton, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Thomas Grantham Alford 